# Data Architecture Rules

This is the authoritative rule for data architecture decisions. If any older document conflicts with this file, follow this file.

## 1) Stats computation (required)

- Closed-sale stats must use closed listings only: `StandardStatus ILIKE '%Closed%'`.
- Closed-sale period filtering must use `CloseDate` windows, not listing on-market dates.
- Sold price metrics must use `ClosePrice` with fallback chain:
  - `COALESCE("ClosePrice", (details->>'ClosePrice')::numeric, "ListPrice")`
- Median metrics must use true medians with ordered-set aggregates:
  - `percentile_cont(0.5) WITHIN GROUP (...)`
- Do not label averages as medians.
- `sale_to_list_ratio` must be computed from price data, never hardcoded.
- Prefer pre-computed summary tables (`market_stats_cache`, `market_pulse_live`) over live scans.

## 2) Geo slug and hierarchy (required)

- Community-level cache keys must use colon-separated slugs:
  - `citySlug:communitySlug`
- Use `subdivisionEntityKey()` for community geo slug generation.
- Never use hyphen-separated `city-community` values for stats cache keys.
- Geography model:
  - City > optional Neighborhood > Community
  - Community equals MLS `SubdivisionName` in user-facing terms.
  - Neighborhood is the broader parent area and may be absent.

## 3) Listing URL contract (required)

- Canonical listing URL:
  - `/homes-for-sale/{city}/[{neighborhood}/]{community}/{address-slug}-{mlsNumber}`
- Segment behavior:
  - Include neighborhood only when defined for the community.
  - Omit community segment when community data is unavailable:
    - `/homes-for-sale/{city}/{address-slug}-{mlsNumber}`
  - Fallback when location data is insufficient:
    - `/homes-for-sale/listing/{mlsNumber}`
- Public listing identifier is `ListNumber` (MLS number).
- `ListingKey` is internal and not canonical in URLs.
- Legacy ListingKey URL shapes must 301 redirect to canonical MLS + address URLs.

## 4) JSONB strategy (required)

- Do not include `details` JSONB in tile/card/list map selects on hot paths.
- Promote frequently queried listing fields to first-class columns when needed.
- Use explicit projection lists; no `select(*)` for user-facing listing queries.

## 5) Query patterns (required)

- Parallelize independent queries with `Promise.all`.
- Do not run sequential waterfalls when queries are independent.
- Deduplicate repeated per-request data reads by sharing fetches.
- Use `React.cache()` where metadata + page fetches share the same dataset.
- Avoid `fetchAllRows` in user-facing hot paths.

## 6) Caching and rendering (required)

- Public pages must define ISR behavior (`revalidate`) unless truly dynamic by requirement.
- Stats and pulse reads must come from cache tables, not ad-hoc aggregations.
- Community-to-neighborhood mapping can be cached and refreshed periodically.

## 7) Performance non-negotiables

- No `select(*)` on listing-heavy paths.
- Cap expensive batch operations (for example geocoding fan-out).
- Keep DB round-trips minimal and avoid duplicated fetches.
- Keep structured data URLs, canonical tags, sitemap URLs, and visible routes aligned.

